node.text: Here’s a super simple full-body complex that will kick your ass in minimal time with minimal equipment. 6 overhead press, 6 front squats, 6 bentover rows, and 6 RDLs, all done in succession without putting the bar down. I don’t like doing the barbell lifts with heavy weights most of the time, but doing them in a complex with lighter weights is cool and allows me to practice the exercises without beating myself up. Did six rounds of this complex and then ran my hill a few times and called it a day. Give it a try.

node.text:
I did this mamma-jamma yesterday and I’m feeling all kinds of spicy today—the good kind of spicy. Start with six seated overhead presses, then adjust the bench to a 45-degree incline and do six incline presses, then make the bench flat and finish with six more presses. If you pick a weight that barely allows you to get six reps on the overhead press, it’ll end up being the perfect weight for the incline and flat bench presses, too. I used the 70s yesterday which is the most weight I’ve ever done on seated overhead presses, so I’m happy about that. I like this mechanical dropset for a few reasons:
***
A lot of guys focus on chest and then hit shoulders as an afterthought; however, for most people’s performance and physique goals, I think it’s better to prioritize shoulders first, and this hits shoulders while you’re fresh.
***
This is a great option for people who don’t have super heavy dumbbells. If you’d normally use 100+ pounds on dumbbell bench press but don’t have dumbbells that big, this works well to work your chest with lighter weights because you won’t be able to go nearly as heavy after doing overhead presses first.
***
A few form/technique notes: on seated overhead presses, I think it’s best to actually set the bench on a slight incline, as it leads to better pressing mechanics and a better back position because almost everyone arches too much when the bench is completely vertical. On the presses themselves, I like either using a neutral grip through, or starting with a neutral grip at the bottom and pronating as you press up.
***
This video probably won’t get many likes because it’s basic and doesn’t look that cool. That’s fine with me, but I do hope you’ll try it because I promise that the basic stuff works better than the wacky, cool-looking exercises that get a lot of likes but don’t usually work so well in real life. That concludes my Ted Talk.

node.text:
Here’s a simple (but awesome) full-body complex that you only need a set of dumbbells or kettlebells to do. I know on social media it’s cool to share exercises that look cool but are so complicated that nobody would actually do them in real life, but this one is the opposite of that: it looks so simple that it’s almost boring, but it’s something that actually works really well that you could go do today and get a good workout. It consists of: five alternating overhead presses/arm, five front-loaded reverse lunges/leg, five bentover Batwing rows/arm, and five single leg RDLs/leg, all done in succession without putting the weights down. That’s it: simple,  practical, and doable—but definitely not easy.
***
We use complexes when we’re short on time, or as a change of pace workout to get a good training effect without going quite as heavy. It’s also a good way to get cardio for people who hate normal cardio. That said, the goal is still to use heavyish weights, and know that the heavier you go, the more it gets your heart rate up. I’ve built up to using 60 pound dumbbells, and after just a few rounds I look like I jumped in the pool with my clothes on.
***
A few notes on the individual exercises that I think/hope will help.
***
Alternating overhead press: Use a neutral grip. Keep the arm that’s up as straight as you can. Squeeze your butt to take pressure off your lower back.
***
Front-loaded reverse lunges: Normally when you see front-loaded dumbbell exercises, people rest the weights on their shoulders. I don’t like that, as it leads to overarching your back. Instead, hold the weights against the front of your body. It leads to a better back position and it’s easier to support the weights, especially heavy ones.
***
Bentover batwing rows: Most people don’t bend over enough on bentover rows and turn it into more of an upright row. Think like you’re trying to get your torso parallel to the floor, without rounding your back.
***
Single leg RDL: It really helps to tilt the dumbbells downward as you descend instead of keeping the weights level. I can’t tell you why this hell’s, but I can tell it’s helped just about everyone I’ve ever trained.

This complex killed me: eight reps each of 1-arm arm press, reverse lunge, 1-arm row, and single leg RDL—all performed in succession without putting the bar down. I use complexes as a way to get cardio without doing traditional boring “gerbil” cardio. They provide a good bang for your buck because it’s a way to build strength, boost conditioning, and burn fat at the same time. A few notes on how to construct your own complex:
***
Start with the hardest exercises, then proceed to easier exercises as you fatigue.
***
Alternate upper body and lower body exercises. This increases the metabolic demand and also gives your upper and lower body short rests so you don’t fatigue as quickly.
***
Chose exercises that flow together smoothly to avoid awkward transitions. Similarly, avoid choosing exercises that require a significant reduction in weight as compared to the other exercises.
***
For a simple full-body template, start with an upper body push, then a knee-dominant lower body exercise, then an upper body pull, then a hip-dominant lower body exercises.
***
Start light to make sure your form is good, but don’t be afraid to load it heavy. Heavier weight cranks your heart rate up more.
***
Wear your big boy/girl pants. This ain’t easy. My big boy pants happen to have polka dots on them.
***
Complexes can be used as a way to perform a full-body workout when you’re short on time, or when you’re not feeling up to training as heavy but still want a good workout. Or it’s good for people like me who hate cardio but know it’s good for you. Enjoy! PS: you won’t enjoy.

Give it a try, and please share with anyone who is stuck at home who you think might benefit from this. PS- the variation I show at the end is really hard: fair warning.

node.text: This is a long video but I hope you’ll watch it because it means a lot to me. Annie Gow is an angel. She was my physical therapist 15 years ago after my botched back surgery, and it was one of the lowest points of my life, both physically and emotionally. I was as depressed as you can be, and truth be told, she was more of a therapist to me than a physical therapist. This is hard for me to share and it brings back a lot of hard memories, but social media tends to be a highlight reel and I want people to know the real. I was in a really dark place and I didn’t see any hope, but tough times can either break you or make you stronger. One of my lowest points ended up being the impetus for the life I have now, and I’m very thankful for Annie and many other amazing people who helped me when I’d almost given up. I hope my story can help other people who are going through hard times because I know what it’s like to be struggling and then go on social media and see everyone else seemingly happy and loving life. Trust me, everyone’s got shit they’re dealing with.

node.text: Today was my last workout with Chelsea before Christmas, so I brought her gift early.

I’m convinced that @tealjackson is part human and part cyborg because she’s so freakin’ strong. Here are three advanced core moves for you to work up to. She makes them all look easy, but they’re all super hard so make sure you don’t jump right into trying them without building up first.
***
Side plank reverse flyes. This is a progression of the side plank pressouts I’ve shown before, and it smokes your obliques. Doing them with one leg like Teal is here is just wild, so start with both feet on the ground. As a reference, she’s using 5 pounds (that’s what I use for this one, too).
***
Hanging lateral leg raises. Another good one for obliques. A lot of you will struggle to hold yourself at the top part of the pull-up, but try it with your arms straight, and/or bend your legs.
***
Standing barbell rollouts. This is actually the hardest of all these exercises, even if it looks simple enough. Definitely start from your knees before doing them standing.

No complacency.

node.text: These uphill walking step-through lunges from @kateupton are badass. This is a really hard exercise on flat ground with just your own bodyweight, let alone going uphill holding two kettlebells in the rack position. Love the effort she brings every workout, and it’s cool to see how strong she’s gotten. Consistent hard work over time goes a lonnnng way. Give this exercise a try if you’re someone who likes to punish themselves. Otherwise, maybe skip it because I won’t lie—it’s a real bitch.

node.text: Here’s a tour of my fridge. If it seems like an ad for @cheribundi, that’s because it is, but I really do like it and think you will too. You’re supposed to drink it after workouts to reduce soreness and improve recovery, and I’ll also just drink it throughout the day when I get sick of water or mix it with adult beverages as a way to feel like I’m being healthy when I’m not being healthy. This video is also making me realize that I should really learn how to cook, and that I need to get my life together a little bit more.

Here’s some of my training from the past few weeks. I’ve been on a big pool workout kick and doing mostly that for upper body, but I still hit the weights a couple times a week, where it’s been predominantly lower body. Can’t be skipping leg day, folks. Here’s a few notes on the individual exercises, and if you have any questions, just ask:
***
Belt Squats: I got the new KBox and it’s both awesome and awful at the same time. The eccentric pull is brutal, but I love how it smokes your legs with no stress on the lower back.
***
Single Leg Squats: I try to do these once a month-ish so I don’t lose my ability to do them well, but if I’m honest, I don’t do them too often because they suck.
***
Dumbbell Front Squats: This has become my preferred way of squatting for me and a lot of my clients. Powerblocks are awesome for most stuff but not for goblet squats, so this is the best way I’ve found to squat with them, and it’s also great for when you’ve maxed out your dumbbells. My heaviest dumbbell is 100 pounds but I’m holding two 70s here for greater loading potential. Definitely give this a try.
***
KBox Squats/Ring-Assisted Jumps: Sometimes I squat on the KBox with the belt, and sometimes I use the handles, which is sort of a deadlift/squat hybrid. As for the jumps, I like to incorporate them in my routine to try to keep (and improve) my bounce, and the rings just dissipate some of the landing stress so it doesn’t piss off my knees.
***
Chest-Supported Barbell Rows: Way less lower back stress than bentover rows, so it’s what I do when I want to row heavy. I prefer a supinated (underhand) grip.
***
Hollow-Body 1-Arm Press: While the press ostensibly seems like an upper body exercise, I’d classify this more as a core exercise. This week I used 70 pounds, which is a personal record for me. Love this one.

As a tribute to The Jersey Shore (one of my favorite tv shows), I’m calling my summer fitness regimen the ‘GTL Routine’: golf, tennis, and lifting. #tshirttime
***
Truth be told, I’d usually rather be outside doing active stuff instead of in the gym, but the work in the gym helps support all that stuff. At different times through the year I prioritize weight training over other stuff, and other times I back off and prioritize other stuff and just train a few times a week. It’s all about balance.

node.text: @phil.rosenthal really needs to get his ears checked.

Here are some snippets of @kellyoubrejr offseason training. He’s a beast and brings the effort every workout. 
***
For my fellow training nerds: Exercise selection differs slightly between all the athletes I train based on their goals, anthropometry, and strengths/weaknesses, but in general I like athletes to have a good blend of knee-dominant and hip-dominant strength, a good blend of bilateral and unilateral strength, and under the umbrella of unilateral work, I like doing a blend of supported single leg exercises (lunges, rear foot elevated split squats, etc) and unsupported single leg exercises (skater squats, single leg RDLs, etc). Under the umbrella of hip-dominant exercises, I like athletes to be proficient with hip extension exercises (RDLs, single leg RDLs), knee flexion based exercises (leg curl variations), and bridging. Add in some frontal plane work and you’re good. Kelly checks all these boxes, which is awesome to see.
